HEADWORD: Tutelary
<hw>Tu"te*la*ry</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>tutelaris</ets>: cf.
F. <ets>tut⟦eacute⟧laire</ets>. See <er>Tutelage</er>.]</ety>
<def>Having the guardianship or charge of protecting a person or a
thing; guardian; protecting; <as>as, <ex>tutelary</ex>
goddesses</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This, of all advantages, is the greatest . . . the most
<qex>tutelary</qex> of morals.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tutele</ent>⟦br⟧
